Through Week 9:
I've tweaked my model a little bit to account for a couple of issue that came up as the number of games left decreased.
5 games into the season; Chiefs currently 4-1; Chargers 3-2; Broncos 2-3 and Raiders 1-4

The Chiefs have Patrick Mahomes and exciting new players on the team, however they're still finding their stride. The Chargers have an excellent QB and have been in contention in recent years, but Mahomes has a proven track record of winning close games. The Broncos have a good team and are learning how to operate with Russell Wilson at QB, but have a talented receiving corps.

I'm using the weighted average of the past and current season winrate to determine the probability distribution for the number of wins at the end of the season using Poisson. Then I'm taking random values from such distribution and simulating 500 seasons to determine the likelihood of each team to win the division.
The Chiefs looked as dominate as every on Sunday. The Broncos revealed some problems I didn't know about before last night.

My initial forecast comes purely from a base rate estimation. I started by analyzing the probability distribution of winrate change from one year to the next and found that 2/3 of the times each team remains within +/- 20% of the winrate of the previous year.
